 {
  "response_text": "The initial risk disposition among social learning agents remains invariant throughout the 100-year simulation period, holding constant at approximately 0.0074 from initialization through year 100. The metric exhibits no temporal variation, maintaining identical values across all observed time steps with zero variance. This stability reflects that the measure captures a fixed, time-independent attribute assigned to social learning agents at model initialization—their baseline attitude toward uncertainty and deviation from recommended livestock levels. Since this represents an initial condition rather than a dynamic state variable, it does not evolve in response to environmental feedback or learning experiences.\n\nImplications for decision makers: The invariant initial risk disposition indicates that the model holds baseline heterogeneity in risk attitudes constant across all social learning agents. This experimental design choice isolates the effects of learning strategies from confounding variation in initial risk preferences, allowing decision makers to attribute observed differences in pasture outcomes or household persistence specifically to the learning mechanisms (social learning, learning-by-doing, or static rule-of-thumb) rather than to varying initial dispositions. Consequently, any divergence in performance between agent types can be clearly linked to their distinct adaptive capacities rather than to pre-existing differences in risk tolerance."
}

